    {
      "content": "Overview",
      "pos": [
        1260,
        1268
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure Web and Business SQL databases run in a shared, multi-tenant environment without any reserved resource capacity for the database.",
      "pos": [
        1274,
        1409
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The activity of other databases within this shared resource environment can impact your performance.",
      "pos": [
        1410,
        1510
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Resource availability at any given point depends heavily on other concurrent workloads running in the system.",
      "pos": [
        1511,
        1620
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This can result in highly varying and unpredictable database application performance.",
      "pos": [
        1621,
        1706
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Customer feedback is that this unpredictable performance is difficult to manage, and more predictable performance is preferred.",
      "pos": [
        1707,
        1834
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To address this feedback, Azure SQL Database service introduced new database service tiers <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>(Basic, Standard and Premium)<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/dn741340.aspx)</ept>, which offer predictable performance and a wealth of new features for business continuity and security.",
      "pos": [
        1837,
        2112
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These new service tiers are designed to provide a specified level of resources for a database workload, regardless of other customer workloads running in that environment.",
      "pos": [
        2113,
        2284
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This results in highly predictable performance behavior.",
      "pos": [
        2285,
        2341
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "With these changes come questions about how to evaluate and decide which new service tier is the best fit for current Web and Business (W/B) databases and about the actual upgrade process.",
      "pos": [
        2344,
        2532
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Ultimately, the best choice is the service tier and performance level combination that provides you the optimum balance between features, performance, and cost, yet one which completely satisfies the business needs and requirements of your application.",
      "pos": [
        2534,
        2786
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This paper provides a guided methodology for upgrading a Web or Business database to one of the new service tiers/performance levels.",
      "pos": [
        2788,
        2921
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "What is important to note, is that Azure SQL Databases are not locked into any specific service tier or performance level, so as the requirements of your database change you can easily change between the available service tiers and performance levels.",
      "pos": [
        2923,
        3174
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In fact, Basic, Standard, and Premium SQL Databases are billed by the hour, and you have the ability to scale each database up or down 4 times within a 24 hour period (using the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Portal or programmatically<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/ff394116.aspx)</ept>).",
      "pos": [
        3175,
        3444
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This means you can adjust the service tier and performance level to maximize your database’s performance needs, feature set, and cost, based on your application’s requirements and varying workload.",
      "pos": [
        3445,
        3642
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This also means that evaluating and changing the service tier and performance level of your database (scaling up and down) is an ongoing process that should be part of your scheduled maintenance and performance tuning routine.",
      "pos": [
        3643,
        3869
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Upgrading Web and Business Databases",
      "pos": [
        3876,
        3912
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Upgrading Web or Business databases to a new service tier/performance level does not take the database offline.",
      "pos": [
